אֱלֹהָי נְשָׁמָה שֶׁ/נָ/SIתַ/תָ /בִי טְהוֹרָה הִיא:/PR

אַ/תָה בְרָאתָ/ה, אַ/תָה יְצַרְ/תָ/ה אַ/תָה נְפַחְ/תָ/ה /בִי וְאַ/תָה מְשַׁ/מְרָ/ה /בְקִרְ/בִי
וְאַ/תָה עָתִיד לִ/טְלָ/ה מִ/SI/מֶ/נִי לְחַ/יֵי עוֹלָם:/PH/PR

/HN/PR

/PR

Elohay neshamah shena/UNta/XXta bi tehorah hi./PR

םלוע ייחל / restoring [the soul] to everlasting life. The traditional Hebrew
text says, "and restore it to me in the future to come." The text in our
siddur, rather than stressing the traditional notion of individual afterlife,
or of personal resurrection in the messianic End of Days, reverses the
emphasis: the soul, having sojourned in the physical life, is restored to the
everlasting stream of life--to the continuum of being that is the sum-total
of all transitory lives, when viewed from the perspective of eternity.    /SC/XXJ.R./XX/PR

/PR

/SCG/XXUIDED /XXM/XXEDITATION/XX. In the Hebrew of המשנ יהלא / My God, the soul,
many of the words end with the sound "ah," spelled "הָ". When this prayer
is chanted slowly, you breathe these words. Thus this prayer suggests an
opportunity, through breathing, to explore the connection between
/ITneshamah/XX as breath and as soul:/PR

/PR

Sit comfortably with your eyes closed, feet uncrossed, and hands loosely
on your lap. Take a series of slow, relaxed breaths. Donòt try to control
them. Just let them come and go freely. Focus your concentration on your
breath. Let the thoughts you have flow through you. Donòt try to control
them. Each time you end a thought, return your focus to your breath. Do
this for several minutes. As you follow your breath, reflect on the divine
energy it contains.    /SC/XXL.W.K./D.B./XX/PR

/PR

/PR

